<paragraph blockId="1.[151,895,762,822]" box="[151,463,797,822]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,259,797,822]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1369,1392]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,363,1346]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,363,1346]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Habitus of Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 1. dorsal view; 2. lateral view; 3. ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321800/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Figs 1–3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[271,330,798,822]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,182,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,173,1505]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 7. head; 8 – 9. mandibles; 10 – 11. antennae; 12. labrum; 13. epipharynx; 14. maxillae and labium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">7–14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[341,371,798,822]" captionStart="FIGURES 23 – 24" captionStartId="7.[151,263,645,668]" captionTargetBox="[509,1080,215,603]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[488,1099,193,624]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23 – 24. Tibia and tarsungulus, last instar larva. 23. Plagiosterna adamsii; 24. P. aenea." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321804/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">23</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[383,454,797,822]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 29" captionStartId="8.[151,263,1728,1751]" captionTargetBox="[239,1351,254,1656]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 29. Schematic presentation of tubercular patterns (top: prothorax; middle: mesothorax; bottom: 2 nd abdominal segment). 25. first instar larva of Plagiosterna adamsii; 26. last instar larva of P. adamsii; 27. first instar larva of P. aenea; 28. last instar larva of P. aenea; 29. color variation of last instar larva of P. aenea." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321805/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">25, 26</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,869,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,374,869,894]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">First instar larva.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[546,717,870,894]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" unit="mm" value="2.2" valueMax="2.3" valueMin="2.1">2.10–2.30 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[813,984,869,894]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.75" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="6.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" unit="mm" value="0.675" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.65">0.65–0.70 mm</quantity>
, head width 
<quantity box="[1146,1253,869,894]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" unit="mm" value="0.58">0.58 mm</quantity>
(n = 2). Body yellowish-white with head dark brown, tubercles and legs brown. Sclerotized platelets on dorsum rather dense, on venter sparse. Defensive glands present on meso- and metathorax and abdominal segments I–VII. Small egg bursters present on meso- and metathorax. Head and mouthparts similar in the shape and chaetotaxy to those of the last instar larva.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,869,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis box="[199,280,1049,1074]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Thorax</emphasis>
. Prothorax with D-DL-EPa (10L 7–11S 4–5M); EPp (1S 2M); P (3S); ES-SS (1S 2M) (
<figureCitation box="[1261,1344,1049,1074]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 29" captionStartId="8.[151,263,1728,1751]" captionTargetBox="[239,1351,254,1656]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 29. Schematic presentation of tubercular patterns (top: prothorax; middle: mesothorax; bottom: 2 nd abdominal segment). 25. first instar larva of Plagiosterna adamsii; 26. last instar larva of P. adamsii; 27. first instar larva of P. aenea; 28. last instar larva of P. aenea; 29. color variation of last instar larva of P. aenea." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321805/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). Meso- and metathorax with Da (2S 3M) sometimes divided into large Dai and small Dae; Dp (1L 1S) smaller than Da; DLi (1L 1S 1–2M) with a very small egg burster situated anterior to a long seta; DLe (1L 4–5S 2M) conical with a defensive gland; EPa (4–5S); EPp (1L 4S); P (2–3S); SS (1M); ES (1S 1M).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,869,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1193,1218]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Segments I–VI with D (1L 5–6S); DL (1L 3–4S) with a defensive gland; EP (1L 5–6S); P (1L 3S); PS-SS (2S 1–2M) generally divided into 2 tubercles; ES (2S) on both sides fused or separated; as1 (1M). Segment VII with D on both sides fused; DL with a defensive gland. Segment VIII with dorsal and dorsolateral tubercles fused. Segment IX with D-DL-EP (3S 5–7M) fused. Segment X with pygopod well developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,869,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,492,1337,1362]" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Third (last) instar larva.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[647,811,1338,1362]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.085" metricValueMax="1.14" metricValueMin="1.03" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" unit="mm" value="10.85" valueMax="11.4" valueMin="10.3">10.3–11.4 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[896,1034,1338,1362]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="3.3" metricValueMin="3.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" unit="mm" value="3.25" valueMax="3.3" valueMin="3.2">3.2–3.3 mm</quantity>
, head width 
<quantity box="[1179,1343,1337,1362]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.21" metricValueMax="1.25" metricValueMin="1.17" pageId="1" pageNumber="382" unit="mm" value="1.21" valueMax="1.25" valueMin="1.17">1.17–1.25 mm</quantity>
(n = 5). Body elongate, widest at abdominal segments II–III and moderately convex dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[1138,1242,1373,1398]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1369,1392]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,363,1346]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,363,1346]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Habitus of Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 1. dorsal view; 2. lateral view; 3. ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321800/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
). Head blackishbrown with mouthparts partially yellowish-white; dorsal tubercles brown to blackish-brown, whereas ventral ones much paler (
<figureCitation box="[293,361,1445,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1369,1392]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,363,1346]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,363,1346]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Habitus of Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 1. dorsal view; 2. lateral view; 3. ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321800/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); dorsal integument brown except median line of thorax on account of very dense and strongly sclerotized platelets, whereas ventral one yellowish-white on account of sparse and weakly sclerotized platelets; legs brown with apex of each segment dark brown. Defensive glands present on meso- and metathorax and abdominal segments I–VII.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,869,2010]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,320]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="383" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis box="[199,260,1589,1614]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Head</emphasis>
. Hypognathous, rounded, strongly sclerotized (
<figureCitation box="[800,870,1589,1614]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,182,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,173,1505]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 7. head; 8 – 9. mandibles; 10 – 11. antennae; 12. labrum; 13. epipharynx; 14. maxillae and labium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Vertex with 4 pairs of minute setae; epicranium with 9 pairs of setae; temporal side of head with 4 pairs of setae. Epicranial suture distinct; frontal suture short, not reaching antennal socket; endocarina well developed. Frons with 4–5 pairs of setae. Clypeus trapezoidal with 3 pairs of setae. Labrum deeply emarginate with 2 pairs of short and 1 pair of minute setae and 2 pairs of campaniform sensilla placed medially and 1 pair of minute setae placed at anterior border (
<figureCitation box="[1201,1287,1733,1758]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,182,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,173,1505]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 7. head; 8 – 9. mandibles; 10 – 11. antennae; 12. labrum; 13. epipharynx; 14. maxillae and labium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
); epipharynx with 3 pairs of stout setae at anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[726,816,1769,1794]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,182,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,173,1505]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 7. head; 8 – 9. mandibles; 10 – 11. antennae; 12. labrum; 13. epipharynx; 14. maxillae and labium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Mandible palmate, 5-toothed, with 2 setae and 2 campaniform sensilla (
<figureCitation box="[424,535,1805,1830]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,182,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,173,1505]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 7. head; 8 – 9. mandibles; 10 – 11. antennae; 12. labrum; 13. epipharynx; 14. maxillae and labium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Figs 8–9</figureCitation>
). Maxillary palp 3-segmented; palpomere I transverse with 1 seta and 1 campaniform sensillum; II rectangular with 2 setae and 1 campaniform sensillum; III subconical with 1 seta, 1 digitiform sensillum and 1 campaniform sensillum on sides and a group of peg-like sensilla at the apex; palpifer distinct with 2 setae (
<figureCitation box="[393,478,1913,1938]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,182,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,173,1505]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 7. head; 8 – 9. mandibles; 10 – 11. antennae; 12. labrum; 13. epipharynx; 14. maxillae and labium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321802/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="382">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Mala rounded with 10 setae and 1 campaniform sensillum; stipes longer than wide with 3 setae; cardo without setae. Labial palp 2-segmented; palpomere I rectangular with 1 minute seta and 1 campaniform sensillum; II subconical with 1 campaniform sensillum on outer side and a group of peg-like sensilla at the apex. Hypopharyngeal area with 3 pairs of setae (2 of them placed internally, not visible on 
<figureCitation box="[1275,1357,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,182,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,173,1505]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 7. head; 8 – 9. mandibles; 10 – 11. antennae; 12. labrum; 13. epipharynx; 14. maxillae and labium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321802/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) and 1 pair of campaniform sensilla. Prementum with 2 pairs of setae; postmentum with spinules on basolateral region, 3 pairs of setae. Stemmata 6 on each side, 4 of them located above antenna and 2 behind antenna. Antenna short, 3- segmented; antenomere I transverse with 2 campaniform sensilla; II stout with a conical sensorium and 6 setae; III subconical with 5 setae and 1 campaniform sensillum (
<figureCitation box="[765,895,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1516,1539]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,182,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,173,1505]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 14. Plagiosterna adamsii, last instar larva. 7. head; 8 – 9. mandibles; 10 – 11. antennae; 12. labrum; 13. epipharynx; 14. maxillae and labium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321802/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Figs 10–11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1300,1369,1392]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321800/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="383" targetBox="[151,1436,363,1346]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1300,1369,1392]" box="[151,1300,1369,1392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,314,1369,1392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">FIGURES 1–3.</emphasis>
Habitus of 
<taxonomicName box="[433,650,1370,1392]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiosterna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adamsii">
<emphasis box="[433,650,1370,1392]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Plagiosterna adamsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, last instar larva. 1. dorsal view; 2. lateral view; 3. ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1431,2032]" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">
<emphasis box="[199,280,1431,1456]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Thorax</emphasis>
. Prothorax with D-DL-EPa (1L 21–26S) largest; EPp (2–3S) small and rounded; P (2S); ES-SS (3–5S) slightly sclerotized (
<figureCitation box="[378,462,1467,1492]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 29" captionStartId="8.[151,263,1728,1751]" captionTargetBox="[239,1351,254,1656]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 29. Schematic presentation of tubercular patterns (top: prothorax; middle: mesothorax; bottom: 2 nd abdominal segment). 25. first instar larva of Plagiosterna adamsii; 26. last instar larva of P. adamsii; 27. first instar larva of P. aenea; 28. last instar larva of P. aenea; 29. color variation of last instar larva of P. aenea." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321805/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Meso- and metathorax with Da (4–5S 1M) generally divided into large Dai and small Dae; Dp (2S) smaller than Da; DLi (3–4S) much smaller than Dp; DLe (1L 7–8S 1M) large and conical with a defensive gland; EPa (3–5S); EPp (1L 2–4S); P (2S); SS (1S) and ES (2–3S) slightly sclerotized. Mesothoracic spiracles annuliform; peritreme fused with EPa. Legs rather stout; tibia with 13 setae; tarsungulus strongly curved, basal tooth well developed, with 1 short seta (
<figureCitation box="[664,747,1611,1636]" captionStart="FIGURES 23 – 24" captionStartId="7.[151,263,645,668]" captionTargetBox="[509,1080,215,603]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[488,1099,193,624]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23 – 24. Tibia and tarsungulus, last instar larva. 23. Plagiosterna adamsii; 24. P. aenea." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/321804/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1431,2032]" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Segments I–VI with D (6–8S) wider than long; DL (1L 3–4S) conical with a defensive gland; EP (1L 4–6S); P (1L 2–4S) smaller than EP; PS-SS (2–3S) sometimes divided into 2–3 tubercles, slightly sclerotized; ES (2S) on both sides fused or separated, slightly sclerotized; as1 (1S) very small. Segment VII with D on both sides fused; DL with a defensive gland. Segments VIII–IX each with dorsal and dorsolateral tubercles fused (2L 6– 7S 2M and 7–8S 2–4M respectively). Segment X with pygopod well developed. Spiracles present on segments I– VIII.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="383" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1431,2032]" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1863,1888]" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The last instar larva of 
<taxonomicName box="[593,834,1863,1888]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiosterna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adamsii">
<emphasis box="[593,834,1863,1888]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">Plagiosterna adamsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[1065,1214,1864,1888]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiosterna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosana">
<emphasis box="[1065,1079,1865,1888]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1094,1214,1864,1888]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">formosana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the dark dorsum on account of strongly sclerotized platelets. However, this species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[1208,1357,1900,1924]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiosterna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosana">
<emphasis box="[1208,1222,1901,1924]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1237,1357,1900,1924]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">formosana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the pronotum entirely pigmented except a narrow median line, abdomen almost completely covered with sclerotized platelets and legs largely brown (median region of pronotum unpigmented, a pair of broad bands on metathorax and abdominal segments I–IV and legs largely yellowish-white in 
<taxonomicName box="[894,1042,2008,2032]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiosterna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosana">
<emphasis box="[894,908,2009,2032]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[922,1042,2008,2032]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="383">formosana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
